\(\renewcommand{\hat}[1]{\widehat{#1}}\)

08_norm_fit_between


  1. Question

    • Learning objective S-ID.A.4: Use the mean and standard deviation of a data set to fit it to a normal distribution and to estimate population percentages. Recognize that there are data sets for which such a procedure is not appropriate. Use calculators, spreadsheets, and tables to estimate areas under the normal curve.

    On an alien planet, you harvested a sample of adult red-legged vultures. You measured their lengths, in centimeters; those measurements are shown below.

    Length (cm)
    104.0
    93.6
    84.2
    94.9
    97.0
    95.6
    88.4
    103.3
    94.1


    Your boss asks you to use a normal approximation of the population to estimate the proportion of adult red-legged vultures with lengths between 88.7 and 93.7 centimeters.

    You say, “But we don’t know the lengths are normally distributed. They could be bimodal, uniform, skewed, or even non-normal-bell shaped. It does not seem appropriate to just assume the lengths of red-legged vultures are normally distributed.”

    Your boss mumbles something about genetics and alleles and how the length is determined by a multitude of factors. She tells you to just do it. You don’t find it super compelling, but then you remember she is your boss. Also, you figure you can at least state the assumptions clearly in the report. Besides, you know that there is a long history of assuming features like lengths and weights are normally distributed.

    To do the normal approximation:

    1. Calculate the sample mean and sample standard deviation.
    2. Assume those sample statistics (\(\bar{x}\) and \(s\)) are good estimates of the corresponding normal-curve parameters (\(\mu\) and \(\sigma\)).
    3. Find the area under the normal curve between 88.7 and 93.7.
    • Approximately what proportion of red-legged vultures have lengths between 88.7 and 93.7 centimeters?

    Solution

    The solution (if you do not round anything until the end) is 0.26, which expressed as a percentage is 26%.

    \[P(88.7<X<93.7) ~=~ 0.2594 ~=~ 25.94\%\]

    First, find the sample statistics:

    • \(\bar{x} = 95.0111111\)
    • \(s=6.2971113\)

    Then, find the area under a normal curve with parameters \(\mu=95.0111111\) and \(\sigma=6.2971113\) between 88.7 and 93.7.

    Personally, I’d set up a spreadsheet to do this for me. To find normal-curve areas, you can use the NORM.DIST function.

    There is a concept that is worth reviewing first. A cumulative distribution function tells you the probability of the distribution producing a value less than (or equal to) a specified boundary. We referred to this as a left area when we found normal probabilities. To find the area BETWEEN two boundaries, we find the difference of two left areas. For example, let \(X\) represent a normal random variable with \(\mu=95.0111111\) and \(\sigma=6.2971113\).

    \[X \sim N(95.01, 6.30)\]

    We can find the left areas (the cumulative probabilities). To find the area left of 88.7, you can use =NORM.DIST(88.7, 95.0111111, 6.2971113, TRUE).

    \[P(X\le 88.7) = 0.1581\]

    plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-1


    To find the area left of 93.7, you can use =NORM.DIST(93.7, 95.0111111, 6.2971113, TRUE).

    \[P(X\le 93.7) = 0.4175\]

    plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-2


    To find the area between the boundaries, find the difference.

    \[P(88.7 \le X \le 93.7) ~=~ 0.4175-0.1581 ~=~ 0.2594\]

    plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-3


    Spreadsheet

    To find normal-curve areas in a spreadsheet, use the NORM.DIST function. This function takes four arguments:

    • \(x\): An upper boundary of the area
    • mean: The normal-curve mean (\(\mu\))
    • standard_deviation: The normal-curve standard deviation (\(\sigma\))
    • cumulative: A boolean set to TRUE to find an area. (If it is set to FALSE, then we get the height of the curve at \(x\), but that is not super useful except to graph the curve.)

    The NORM.DIST function returns the area under the normal curve from \(-\infty\) to the given boundary.

    A B C D E
    1 length (cm) xbar (sample mean) b1 (lower boundary) P(X<b1) P(b1<X<b2)
    2 104.00 =AVERAGE(A:A) 88.7 =NORM.DIST(C2,B2,B5,TRUE) =D5-D2
    3 93.60
    4 84.20 s (sample standard deviation) b2 (upper boundary) P(X<b2)
    5 94.90 =STDEV(A:A) 93.7 =NORM.DIST(C5,B2,B5,TRUE)
    6 97.00
    7 95.60
    8 88.40
    9 103.30
    10 94.10

    On an alien planet, you harvested a sample of adult green-toed sparrows. You measured their lengths, in centimeters; those measurements are shown below.

    Length (cm)
    48.0
    45.9
    45.9
    60.6
    47.4


    Your boss asks you to use a normal approximation of the population to estimate the proportion of adult green-toed sparrows with lengths between 43.5 and 54.8 centimeters.

    You say, “But we don’t know the lengths are normally distributed. They could be bimodal, uniform, skewed, or even non-normal-bell shaped. It does not seem appropriate to just assume the lengths of green-toed sparrows are normally distributed.”

    Your boss mumbles something about genetics and alleles and how the length is determined by a multitude of factors. She tells you to just do it. You don’t find it super compelling, but then you remember she is your boss. Also, you figure you can at least state the assumptions clearly in the report. Besides, you know that there is a long history of assuming features like lengths and weights are normally distributed.

    To do the normal approximation:

    1. Calculate the sample mean and sample standard deviation.
    2. Assume those sample statistics (\(\bar{x}\) and \(s\)) are good estimates of the corresponding normal-curve parameters (\(\mu\) and \(\sigma\)).
    3. Find the area under the normal curve between 43.5 and 54.8.
    • Approximately what proportion of green-toed sparrows have lengths between 43.5 and 54.8 centimeters?

    Solution

    The solution (if you do not round anything until the end) is 0.63, which expressed as a percentage is 63%.

    \[P(43.5<X<54.8) ~=~ 0.6337 ~=~ 63.37\%\]

    First, find the sample statistics:

    • \(\bar{x} = 49.56\)
    • \(s=6.2404327\)

    Then, find the area under a normal curve with parameters \(\mu=49.56\) and \(\sigma=6.2404327\) between 43.5 and 54.8.

    Personally, I’d set up a spreadsheet to do this for me. To find normal-curve areas, you can use the NORM.DIST function.

    There is a concept that is worth reviewing first. A cumulative distribution function tells you the probability of the distribution producing a value less than (or equal to) a specified boundary. We referred to this as a left area when we found normal probabilities. To find the area BETWEEN two boundaries, we find the difference of two left areas. For example, let \(X\) represent a normal random variable with \(\mu=49.56\) and \(\sigma=6.2404327\).

    \[X \sim N(49.56, 6.24)\]

    We can find the left areas (the cumulative probabilities). To find the area left of 43.5, you can use =NORM.DIST(43.5, 49.56, 6.2404327, TRUE).

    \[P(X\le 43.5) = 0.1658\]

    plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-1


    To find the area left of 54.8, you can use =NORM.DIST(54.8, 49.56, 6.2404327, TRUE).

    \[P(X\le 54.8) = 0.7995\]

    plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-2


    To find the area between the boundaries, find the difference.

    \[P(43.5 \le X \le 54.8) ~=~ 0.7995-0.1658 ~=~ 0.6337\]

    plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-3


    Spreadsheet

    To find normal-curve areas in a spreadsheet, use the NORM.DIST function. This function takes four arguments:

    • \(x\): An upper boundary of the area
    • mean: The normal-curve mean (\(\mu\))
    • standard_deviation: The normal-curve standard deviation (\(\sigma\))
    • cumulative: A boolean set to TRUE to find an area. (If it is set to FALSE, then we get the height of the curve at \(x\), but that is not super useful except to graph the curve.)

    The NORM.DIST function returns the area under the normal curve from \(-\infty\) to the given boundary.

    A B C D E
    1 length (cm) xbar (sample mean) b1 (lower boundary) P(X<b1) P(b1<X<b2)
    2 48.00 =AVERAGE(A:A) 43.5 =NORM.DIST(C2,B2,B5,TRUE) =D5-D2
    3 45.90
    4 45.90 s (sample standard deviation) b2 (upper boundary) P(X<b2)
    5 60.60 =STDEV(A:A) 54.8 =NORM.DIST(C5,B2,B5,TRUE)
    6 47.40




  8. Question

    • Learning objective S-ID.A.4: Use the mean and standard deviation of a data set to fit it to a normal distribution and to estimate population percentages. Recognize that there are data sets for which such a procedure is not appropriate. Use calculators, spreadsheets, and tables to estimate areas under the normal curve.
